RABIES, BOVINE, EATEN - BOLIVIA
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
[see: Rabies prevention in humans: website
<http://www.cdc.gov/epo/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00056176.htm> ]
[1]
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1999 07:55:51 -0400
From: "Gavin Macgregor-Skinner" <gavin@mail.zuper.net>

I have been informed this morning (19 Aug 1999) that a community
in a remote part of Bolivia may have eaten meat from a rabid cow.
It was reported by a veterinarian that 3 cows had died or were killed
after showing clinical signs of rabies. The meat was salted and
dried in the sun and has been consumed; the meat was not
cooked. It is possible that at least 40 people may have eaten the
meat.
The veterinarian has reported today that in the area there are some
cows showing incoordination of the hindquarters. It is known that
there are vampire bats in this area and some cattle have bat bites.
The 3 cows that died had bite wounds on the neck. There have
been no samples submitted for laboratory diagnosis as yet due to
the remoteness of the area.
Myself and another veterinarian from UNIVEP will be travelling to
the area on Saturday to investigate the situation. A community
meeting has been arranged for Sunday evening as it has been
reported that many people in the area are "afraid".
If the cows had rabies and the meat was not cooked but salted and
dried in the sun and then consumed, is this population at risk?
--
Dr Gavin Macgregor-Skinner BVSc MSc MRCVS
