[2]
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1999 11:16:10 -0500
From: "Tam Garland" <TGARLAND@cvm.tamu.edu>

I called the Meat Safety Assurance Agency, a division within the
Texas Dept of Health, for a correct answer. The response was, in
the United States the law says animals showing neurological
conditions are not to be consumed. In the event that a known rabid
animal (like a skunk) bites a cow and the cow is slaughtered in the
first 3-5 days before neurological signs appear then that is OK.
However, I inquired directly regarding the animals showing clinical
signs, and [people] needing the protein, food etc. The answer was:
*Thoroughly* [emphasis by Mod.JW] dried and salted meat should
present NO risk to the consumer since gastric acid should kill any
remaining virus that was not killed by salting and drying.
However, the real risk is to the processors -- those who cut up the
animal. Did they take off the head, did they cut out the spinal
cord? Those persons may be most at risk if the answer is yes.
--
Tam Garland
ProMED-mail Animal Disease and Zoonoses Moderator
College of Veterinary Medicine
Texas A&M University
College Station, TX, USA
tgarland@cvm.tamu.edu
