[3]
Date sent: Fri, 20 Aug 1999 13:22:07 -0400
From: Chuck Trimarchi <trimarch@wadsworth.org>

I don't disagree significantly with the conclusions in the [previous]
reply. The meat (muscle) of an animal killed during clinical rabies
would not be expected to contain much rabies virus (although details of
the pantropism of the vampire bat variant of rabies virus in other
species are not thoroughly described). Consumption or other exposure
to CNS and salivary gland tissue would be another matter. The effect of
gastric acid is not so relevant, due to exposures that could occur in the
buccal cavity due to mucous membranes or existing lesions that could
be present in the mouth while ingesting the meat. *Thorough*
[emphasis - Mod.JW] cooking, or *thorough* salting and drying,
would certainly inactivate rabies virus, due to its labile character.
However, we would not recommend knowingly butchering or
consuming animals suspected of clinical rabies, or for that matter, those
that had demonstrated signs of any neurologic infection. I certainly
concur that the persons slaughtering and butchering these animals, and
particularly those that may have handled the CNS or salivary glands,
need careful evaluation for the need for postexposure management.
Our [NY State] recommendations for the use of tissues from an animal
known to be bitten by a rabid animal do permit slaughter and
consumption of the meat, providing the animal is killed within SEVEN
days of the EXPOSURE, and providing that liberal portions of the
exposed areas are discarded.
--
Chuck Trimarchi
Director, Rabies Laboratory
Wadsworth Center
New York State Health Dept.
Albany, NY, USA
<trimarch@wadsworth.org>
[Note: these replies were sent directly to Gavin, so that he did not have
to wait until they were posted to see the information - Mod.JW]
